INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, content) VALUES (1, 'EECS 485 Final Exam Fall 2025 SOLUTION This is a 120 minute, closed-book exam. You may use one cheat sheet, 8.5”x11”, double-sided. No other notes or use of any computing or communication hardware (e.g., calculators, cell phones, smart glasses, etc.) is allowed. For multiple-choice questions, indicate your response by filling in the appropriate bubble. Fill in the bubble completely, and make sure to erase completely if you change your answer. For free response questions, write your answers clearly in the space provided in each problem. Collaboration or assistance is prohibited ● You are NOT allowed to collaborate with anyone else to answer these questions. ● You are NOT allowed to solicit assistance from anyone to answer these questions. You are to abide by the University of Michigan/Engineering Honor Code. To receive a grade, please sign below to signify that you have kept the honor code pledge. I have neither given nor received aid on this exam, nor have I concealed any violations of the Honor Code. Signature: _________________________________________ Name: _________________________________________ Uniqname: _________________________________________ UMID: _________________________________________ Page 1 of 22 Make sure to write your uniqname at the top of every page of the exam. This page is intentionally left blank Multiple Choice (40 points) Demo Question: How should I fill in my responses for a Multiple Choice question? ⬤ A. Fill in the chosen bubble completely and only select ONE per question! 1. A client is streaming data from a server over TCP, and suddenly packets are dropped due to network congestion. Which outcome is most consistent with how TCP behaves? ◯ A. Some data may be permanently lost ◯ B. The number of ACK packets will increase compared to the number of data packets ◯ C. The number of ACK packets will stay the same as before the congestion ◯ D. The sender''s congestion window will grow ◯ E. The sender’s congestion window will shrink Solution: E. When congestion increases, TCP’s congestion control algorithm reacts by shrinking the congestion window, which reduces the sender’s sending rate. The connection still stays alive. Choices A, C, and D are wrong since TCP will still guarantee reliable, in-order delivery (no loss, no skipping, no out-of-order delivery) to the application. TCP also never switches protocols, making Choice B wrong as well. 2. An online multiplayer game experiences a problem where player positions appear to "jump" on screen rather than moving smoothly. Investigation reveals that when packet 50 is lost, packets 51-70 arrive but aren''t processed until packet 50 is retransmitted. Which networking concept is the most responsible for this behavior? ◯ A. UDP ◯ B. Congestion control ◯ C. IP ◯ D. TCP ◯ E. Flow Control Solution: D, TCP Enforces ordered delivery so if packet 50 is missing, then later packets are buffered and withheld until 50 is retransmitted. shingle size 𝑘 (e.g., moving from 2-shingles to 10-shingles) affect similarity detection? ◯ A. More documents appear similar ◯ B. Fewer documents appear similar ◯ C. Only affects the speed of computation. ◯ D. Increases the probability of hash collisions in MinHash ◯ E. Allows the detection of duplicates even if the words are in a different order. Solution:B. Increasing (k) makes each shingle a longer exact phrase, so small edits affect many shingles and the similarity drops. In other words, a larger shingle size means documents must contain larger sections that match exactly. 4. You are calculating the TF-IDF weight for the term "kangaroo." In which scenario does this term receive the highest weight in a specific document D? ◯ A. "Kangaroo" appears once in D and appears in all other documents in');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, content) VALUES (1, 'when packet 50 is lost, packets 51-70 arrive but aren''t processed until packet 50 is retransmitted. Which networking concept is the most responsible for this behavior? ◯ A. UDP ◯ B. Congestion control ◯ C. IP ◯ D. TCP ◯ E. Flow Control Solution: D, TCP Enforces ordered delivery so if packet 50 is missing, then later packets are buffered and withheld until 50 is retransmitted. shingle size 𝑘 (e.g., moving from 2-shingles to 10-shingles) affect similarity detection? ◯ A. More documents appear similar ◯ B. Fewer documents appear similar ◯ C. Only affects the speed of computation. ◯ D. Increases the probability of hash collisions in MinHash ◯ E. Allows the detection of duplicates even if the words are in a different order. Solution:B. Increasing (k) makes each shingle a longer exact phrase, so small edits affect many shingles and the similarity drops. In other words, a larger shingle size means documents must contain larger sections that match exactly. 4. You are calculating the TF-IDF weight for the term "kangaroo." In which scenario does this term receive the highest weight in a specific document D? ◯ A. "Kangaroo" appears once in D and appears in all other documents in the collection. ◯ B. "Kangaroo" appears frequently in D and appears in all other documents in the collection. ◯ C. "Kangaroo" appears once in D and is very rare in the rest of the collection. ◯ D. "Kangaroo" appears frequently in D and is very rare in the rest of the collection. ◯ E. "Kangaroo" does not appear in D Solution:D. TF-IDF is biggest when the term shows up many times in D (high TF) but is rare across the whole collection (high IDF). 5. Suppose a new website links to every other website but receives no incoming links. What will most likely happen after recomputing PageRank to convergence? ◯ A. Every other page gets a large PageRank boost ◯ B. PageRank values of existing pages barely change ◯ C. The new page accumulates high PageRank ◯ D. Pages with many incoming links will gain significantly more PageRank than pages with few ◯ E. The dampening factor will change to compensate links, so it has almost no PageRank to give out. Even though it links to every page, it’s spreading a tiny amount of rank across many outgoing edges, so nothing really changes. 6. Why might a programmer choose processes over threads? ◯ A. Processes execute faster than threads ◯ B. Processes can share data more easily ◯ C. Processes provide isolation to limit damage from buggy or untrusted code ◯ D. Processes work better for I/O-bound workloads ◯ E. Processes don''t require synchronization primitives for shared data structures Solution: C. Processes have separate address spaces, so bugs or crashes are contained; threads share memory and can corrupt the whole process without careful synchronization. 7. A user visits example.com. Later, the IP address changes, but their next visit still goes to the old server. Why? ◯ A. The user’s browser always stores DNS permanently ◯ B. DNS resolvers cache TTL records ◯ C. The iterative DNS resolution algorithm stops after a cache hit for an NS record ◯ D. DNS caches only root nameserver data ◯ E. DNS resolvers cache A records until their TTL expires Solution: E. DNS caching respects TTL, so results persist until expiration. 8. Which is a key distinction between HITS and PageRank? ◯ A. PageRank computes two scores (hub & authority), HITS computes one ◯ B. HITS is query-dependent; PageRank is query-independent ◯ C. PageRank requires no normalization; HITS does not normalize ◯ D. HITS');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, content) VALUES (1, 'over threads? ◯ A. Processes execute faster than threads ◯ B. Processes can share data more easily ◯ C. Processes provide isolation to limit damage from buggy or untrusted code ◯ D. Processes work better for I/O-bound workloads ◯ E. Processes don''t require synchronization primitives for shared data structures Solution: C. Processes have separate address spaces, so bugs or crashes are contained; threads share memory and can corrupt the whole process without careful synchronization. 7. A user visits example.com. Later, the IP address changes, but their next visit still goes to the old server. Why? ◯ A. The user’s browser always stores DNS permanently ◯ B. DNS resolvers cache TTL records ◯ C. The iterative DNS resolution algorithm stops after a cache hit for an NS record ◯ D. DNS caches only root nameserver data ◯ E. DNS resolvers cache A records until their TTL expires Solution: E. DNS caching respects TTL, so results persist until expiration. 8. Which is a key distinction between HITS and PageRank? ◯ A. PageRank computes two scores (hub & authority), HITS computes one ◯ B. HITS is query-dependent; PageRank is query-independent ◯ C. PageRank requires no normalization; HITS does not normalize ◯ D. HITS uses a damping factor; PageRank does not ◯ E. PageRank looks only at outgoing edges; HITS looks only at incoming edges query-independent. 9. Which Python function is used to prevent busy-waiting? ◯ A. threading.Thread.join() ◯ B. socket.socket.listen() ◯ C. socket.socket.settimeout() ◯ D. socket.socket.setsockopt() ◯ E. time.sleep() Solution: E. time.sleep() is the only function of these that can be used in a loop to yield control to the operating system to switch tasks. 10. Which of the following about the MapReduce framework in Project 4 is FALSE? ◯ A. The manager and workers can be on different computers, so long as they share a file system ◯ B. Reducer executables can be written in C++ ◯ C. The contents of each input file to the reducers must be in sorted order ◯ D. The pipeline produces the same number of output files as the number of mappers ◯ E. If any worker is performing mapping, no other worker can be performing reducing Solution: D. The pipeline produces the same number of output files as the number of reducers , not mappers. C is true, because the mappers are responsible for sorting all their output files, which become the input files to the reducers. See the P4 spec section at 11. You have an inverted index with 1,000 terms and 20,000 documents. You are segmenting this index between 10 servers. Which of the following are TRUE? ◯ A. When segmenting by term, each server will be responsible for 1,000 terms ◯ B. When segmenting by term, each server will be responsible for 2,000 documents ◯ C. When segmenting by document, each server will be responsible for 100 terms documents ◯ E. When segmenting by document, each server will be responsible for 1,000 terms Solution: E. When segmenting by document, each server is responsible for every term, but not every document. 12. A company uses round-robin DNS to distribute requests across three servers. Suddenly, one server becomes overloaded while the others remain idle. Which explanation best accounts for this imbalance? ◯ A. Round-robin DNS changes the HTML structure of responses ◯ B. The DNS system is randomly dropping packets ◯ C. Round-robin DNS does not consider per-request computational load ◯ D. Threads inside the busy server are blocking DNS rotation ◯ E. DNS always sends 90% of traffic to the first IP in its rotation Solution: C. DNS has no way of knowing');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, content) VALUES (1, 'the reducers. See the P4 spec section at 11. You have an inverted index with 1,000 terms and 20,000 documents. You are segmenting this index between 10 servers. Which of the following are TRUE? ◯ A. When segmenting by term, each server will be responsible for 1,000 terms ◯ B. When segmenting by term, each server will be responsible for 2,000 documents ◯ C. When segmenting by document, each server will be responsible for 100 terms documents ◯ E. When segmenting by document, each server will be responsible for 1,000 terms Solution: E. When segmenting by document, each server is responsible for every term, but not every document. 12. A company uses round-robin DNS to distribute requests across three servers. Suddenly, one server becomes overloaded while the others remain idle. Which explanation best accounts for this imbalance? ◯ A. Round-robin DNS changes the HTML structure of responses ◯ B. The DNS system is randomly dropping packets ◯ C. Round-robin DNS does not consider per-request computational load ◯ D. Threads inside the busy server are blocking DNS rotation ◯ E. DNS always sends 90% of traffic to the first IP in its rotation Solution: C. DNS has no way of knowing what a server''s load is. 13. Which scenario best justifies database sharding rather than replication? ◯ A. Data fits easily on a single machine ◯ B. Most queries require consistent reads ◯ C. Reads vastly outnumber writes ◯ D. The dataset is too large to store multiple complete copies ◯ E. The network frequently partitions Solution: D - When the dataset is too large to store full copies, you’re forced to partition it across machines, which is exactly what sharding provides. Replication doesn’t solve storage limits, it only increases redundancy and read throughput. 14. A distributed database is designed so that if a partition occurs, the system returns errors rather than stale data. This design choice implies: ◯ A. The system is sharded rather than replicated ◯ B. The system has both consistency and availability ◯ C. The system is violating the CAP theorem ◯ D. Availability is chosen over consistency ◯ E. Consistency is chosen over availability communicate) certain nodes are updated while others aren’t. Choosing to return an error instead of potentially stale data enforces consistency. 15. A recommender system uses a nearest-neighbor algorithm with cosine similarity. The developer does not normalize the vectors. What will the difference be compared to an implementation that did normalize the vectors? ◯ A. Users who rate more items will be selected as a nearest neighbor more often ◯ B. Users who rate fewer items will be selected as a nearest neighbor more often ◯ C. Items rated fewer times will be recommended more often ◯ D. Items with more ratings will be recommended more often ◯ E. There will be no difference Solution: E. The operations needed to compute cosine similarity can be simplified by normalizing the vectors, but the result will be the same whether or not they were normalized. See DeOrio-Live lecture 15 slides 36-37, Almomani lecture 15 slides 43-44, Kloosterman lecture 15 slide 44. 16. Why would a recommender system use inverse user frequency in its computations? ◯ A. Users that rate few items give more valuable information ◯ B. Users prefer recommendations that are given to few other users ◯ C. It prevents extreme content from being recommended to too many users ◯ D. It is a fundamental part of content-based filtering ◯ E. It helps recommend items that only a small community of users has rated Solution: E - Inverse user frequency down-weights items that many');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, content) VALUES (1, 'be compared to an implementation that did normalize the vectors? ◯ A. Users who rate more items will be selected as a nearest neighbor more often ◯ B. Users who rate fewer items will be selected as a nearest neighbor more often ◯ C. Items rated fewer times will be recommended more often ◯ D. Items with more ratings will be recommended more often ◯ E. There will be no difference Solution: E. The operations needed to compute cosine similarity can be simplified by normalizing the vectors, but the result will be the same whether or not they were normalized. See DeOrio-Live lecture 15 slides 36-37, Almomani lecture 15 slides 43-44, Kloosterman lecture 15 slide 44. 16. Why would a recommender system use inverse user frequency in its computations? ◯ A. Users that rate few items give more valuable information ◯ B. Users prefer recommendations that are given to few other users ◯ C. It prevents extreme content from being recommended to too many users ◯ D. It is a fundamental part of content-based filtering ◯ E. It helps recommend items that only a small community of users has rated Solution: E - Inverse user frequency down-weights items that many have rated and up-weights items that a small group have rated. 17. In a sealed-bid, second-price auction, you value an item at $100. Your research suggests other bidders value it between $60-$120. A consultant advises you to bid $85 to "split the difference and maximize expected profit." Why is this advice flawed? ◯ A. You should bid higher ($120) to ensure you win against the strongest competitor ◯ B. The advice ignores that your bid doesn''t affect whether you win, only what you pay item less than you ◯ D. You should randomize your bid to prevent strategic behavior ◯ E. The correct strategy is to bid $0.01 below your true value Solution: C - In a sealed-bid second-price auction, the optimal strategy is to bid the item''s value. 18. Which part of the Bitcoin system uses public-key cryptography? ◯ A. Linking blocks to previous blocks in the chain ◯ B. Verifying transfers were authorized by the sender ◯ C. Verifying the same coins were not spent twice ◯ D. Hashing blocks to determine which miner can add a block ◯ E. Encrypting private wallets'' transaction history Solution: B - Senders sign transactions with their private key to show they authorize the transaction. A does not use cryptography. C uses the longest-chain consensus. D uses a cryptographic hash (sha256), but hashes are not public-key cryptography. There is no such thing as a private wallet for option E. 19. The Bitcoin protocol requires miners to perform Proof-of-Work computations. What is the primary security purpose of this mechanism? ◯ A. It encrypts the transaction history to make it impossible to change ◯ B. It increases the transaction throughput of the network by parallelizing the verification process across millions of GPUs ◯ C. It validates the identity of the sender more times ◯ D. It makes it prohibitively expensive to create blocks containing double spends ◯ E. It makes it prohibitively expensive to forge an alternate history of the blockchain Solution: E - To forge an alternate history by adding many blocks, proof-of-work requires an attacker to control a large portion of all the mining power in the system. identifying and blocking all Tor entry nodes. However, even after blocking thousands of known entry nodes, citizens continue accessing Tor. What property of Tor''s design makes this approach difficult? ◯ A. The government needs to block exit nodes instead ◯ B. Tor nodes are');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, content) VALUES (1, 'authorize the transaction. A does not use cryptography. C uses the longest-chain consensus. D uses a cryptographic hash (sha256), but hashes are not public-key cryptography. There is no such thing as a private wallet for option E. 19. The Bitcoin protocol requires miners to perform Proof-of-Work computations. What is the primary security purpose of this mechanism? ◯ A. It encrypts the transaction history to make it impossible to change ◯ B. It increases the transaction throughput of the network by parallelizing the verification process across millions of GPUs ◯ C. It validates the identity of the sender more times ◯ D. It makes it prohibitively expensive to create blocks containing double spends ◯ E. It makes it prohibitively expensive to forge an alternate history of the blockchain Solution: E - To forge an alternate history by adding many blocks, proof-of-work requires an attacker to control a large portion of all the mining power in the system. identifying and blocking all Tor entry nodes. However, even after blocking thousands of known entry nodes, citizens continue accessing Tor. What property of Tor''s design makes this approach difficult? ◯ A. The government needs to block exit nodes instead ◯ B. Tor nodes are constantly being added and removed ◯ C. Any Tor node can act as an exit node ◯ D. Blocking Tor nodes would also block legitimate VPN services, causing economic damage ◯ E. Encryption prevents VPN traffic from being detected Solution: B - Tor nodes are dynamically added and removed. A and C do not reflect the structure of the Tor network. D is not true because the IPs of Tor entry nodes are published, allowing other VPNs to not be blocked. E is not true because the destination IP of packets must be unencrypted even when the payload is. Free Response 1: Pie-ority Manager 485 (30 points) The Cats of the Grand Pie Consortium have hired you to manage their distributed pie-baking system. Each pie-baking request is a job with priority HIGH or LOW . HIGH-priority pies must always be baked before LOW-priority pies. You will implement a Manager that assigns jobs to Workers while respecting Priority Rules : ● If no Workers are available to process a new HIGH-priority job, the Manager must cancel a running LOW-priority job so that the HIGH-priority job can be processed. ● Cancelled jobs must be restarted later— unless the Worker finishes the job before the cancel request arrives. When this occurs, the manager may still receive a job_completed message for a job it intended to cancel; in that case, treat it as completed and do not restart it . ● You must receive confirmation that a canceled job has been cancelled or completed before launching it again. A worker will ever only send one of job_completed and job_cancelled for a given job. ● A worker cannot be assigned a new job until it has messaged the manager that the current job was completed or cancelled . ● You may not cancel more jobs than the number of HIGH-priority jobs, and you must not cancel a job if there are enough idle workers to run the incoming jobs. Threading Requirements Your Manager must use two threads total (including the main thread): TCP Listening Thread : ● Runs the provided tcp_server function, forwarding received messages to handle_tcp . ● Updates internal state for the main thread to act upon. Main Thread : ● Start the TCP listening thread. ● Continuously assign jobs to Workers as per the Priority Rules . Avoid busy waiting wherever possible. Simplifying Assumptions: ● Jobs of the same priority may be');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, content) VALUES (1, 'before the cancel request arrives. When this occurs, the manager may still receive a job_completed message for a job it intended to cancel; in that case, treat it as completed and do not restart it . ● You must receive confirmation that a canceled job has been cancelled or completed before launching it again. A worker will ever only send one of job_completed and job_cancelled for a given job. ● A worker cannot be assigned a new job until it has messaged the manager that the current job was completed or cancelled . ● You may not cancel more jobs than the number of HIGH-priority jobs, and you must not cancel a job if there are enough idle workers to run the incoming jobs. Threading Requirements Your Manager must use two threads total (including the main thread): TCP Listening Thread : ● Runs the provided tcp_server function, forwarding received messages to handle_tcp . ● Updates internal state for the main thread to act upon. Main Thread : ● Start the TCP listening thread. ● Continuously assign jobs to Workers as per the Priority Rules . Avoid busy waiting wherever possible. Simplifying Assumptions: ● Jobs of the same priority may be executed in any order. ● Workers do not die and will always eventually respond to all messages. All messages will be delivered. ● All messages received are well formatted. class members def tcp_client(host, port, msg): """ Creates a socket connection to (host, port) and sends the msg dictionary. """ def tcp_server(host, port, handler, signals): """ Listens for TCP connections on (host, port) and receives messages until signals["shutdown"] is set to True. When a message is received, handler(msg) is called, where msg is a dictionary. """ Managers can receive the following messages via TCP : From a client: { "type": "launch_job", "priority": “HIGH” | “LOW”, "command": <string> } From worker: { "type": "register", "host": <string>, "port": <int> } From a worker: { "type": "job_completed", "job_id": <int> } From a worker: { "type": "job_cancelled", "job_id": <int> } Managers can send the following messages via TCP: To a worker: { "type": "start_job", "job_id": <int>, "command": <string> } To a worker: { "type": "cancel_job", "job_id": <int> } methods function correctly as specified , regardless of your implementation details. Note that these are class members. You do not need to add member variables that support these functions. def assign_job_to_worker(self, host, port, job_id, command: str): """ Assign a job to a worker and send the start_job message. """ def find_running_low_job(self): """ Returns (worker host, worker port, job_id) for a LOW priority job currently assigned to a worker, or (None, None, None) if none found. A job is still running even if you have sent a cancel message to its worker. """ class Manager: def __init__(self, host: str, port: int): self.signals = {"shutdown": False} self.idle_workers = set() # Set of (host, port) tuples self.next_job_id = 0 self.low_queue = [] # list of job_ids of low priority jobs # Add additional data structures here, if necessary self.high_queue = [] # List of job_ids self.cancelling = set() # Set of job_ids self.job_commands = {} # job_id -> command tcp_thread = threading.Thread( target=tcp_server, args=(host, port, self.handle_tcp, self.signals) ) tcp_thread.start() self.assign_jobs() # Write implementation below tcp_thread.join() while not self.signals["shutdown"]: # if we have HIGH jobs waiting, but no idle workers, cancel a low # priority job and assign it to the worker. if self.high_queue and not self.idle_workers and \ len(self.cancelling) < len(self.high_queue): # We are assuming that self.find_running_low_job() # does not return the same job_id every time. Student solutions # were allowed to make that same assumption. host, port, low_job_id =');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, content) VALUES (1, 'Assign a job to a worker and send the start_job message. """ def find_running_low_job(self): """ Returns (worker host, worker port, job_id) for a LOW priority job currently assigned to a worker, or (None, None, None) if none found. A job is still running even if you have sent a cancel message to its worker. """ class Manager: def __init__(self, host: str, port: int): self.signals = {"shutdown": False} self.idle_workers = set() # Set of (host, port) tuples self.next_job_id = 0 self.low_queue = [] # list of job_ids of low priority jobs # Add additional data structures here, if necessary self.high_queue = [] # List of job_ids self.cancelling = set() # Set of job_ids self.job_commands = {} # job_id -> command tcp_thread = threading.Thread( target=tcp_server, args=(host, port, self.handle_tcp, self.signals) ) tcp_thread.start() self.assign_jobs() # Write implementation below tcp_thread.join() while not self.signals["shutdown"]: # if we have HIGH jobs waiting, but no idle workers, cancel a low # priority job and assign it to the worker. if self.high_queue and not self.idle_workers and \ len(self.cancelling) < len(self.high_queue): # We are assuming that self.find_running_low_job() # does not return the same job_id every time. Student solutions # were allowed to make that same assumption. host, port, low_job_id = self.find_running_low_job() if host and (low_job_id not in self.cancelling): self.cancelling.add(low_job_id) tcp_client( host, port, {"type": "cancel_job", "job_id": low_job_id}, ) # Note this solution only cancels one job at a time, but # can cancel additional jobs next time around the while loop. if self.idle_workers and (self.high_queue or self.low_queue): if self.high_queue: job_id = self.high_queue.pop(0) elif self.low_queue: job_id = self.low_queue.pop(0) worker = self.idle_workers.pop() command = self.job_commands[job_id] self.assign_job_to_worker(worker[0], worker[1], job_id, command) time.sleep(0.1) elif message["type"] == "job_cancelled": job_id = message["job_id"] # Add worker back to idle pool. You can assume this member function # is implemented for you and works correctly. worker = self.find_worker_by_job_id(job_id) self.idle_workers.add(worker) # successfully cancelled, remove from cancelling set self.cancelling.remove(job_id) # put job back in queue (restart it) # HIGH jobs can''t be cancelled, so the job must be LOW priority self.low_queue.append(job_id) Free Response 2: Speedy Speedy Robots (30 points) eecs485staff has partnered with a local warehouse robot provider to analyze robot movement efficiency! Write a two-stage MapReduce pipeline that identifies the average transition time between warehouse zones and determines which robots are moving the slowest for each transition path. Input map1.py will receive warehouse log file entries in the following format: <robot_id> <timestamp> <zone> <event> Example input: r2 700.0 produce load r2 800.0 dairy unload r1 100.0 bakery load r2 100.0 freezer load r1 200.0 bakery unload r1 900.0 produce load r1 1005.0 dairy unload r2 600.0 bakery unload robot_id: unique robot identifier represented as the prefix "r" with a number timestamp: timestamp (in minutes since start) zone: the warehouse zone the event is happening in event: "load" or "unload" Stage 1 The first stage must identify all zone transitions for each robot and calculate the duration of each transition . A zone transition occurs when a robot unloads in a different zone than where it loaded. It also occurs when a robot moves from a zone it unloaded into a different zone to load. Loading and unloading in the same zone is not a zone transition, nor is loading in the same zone that the robot was unloaded in. The transition duration is calculated as the difference between the timestamp when the robot arrives at the new zone and the timestamp when it was last seen in the previous zone. You may assume loading always happens prior in time to unloading for a given robot, and that every unload is preceded in time by exactly one load. However, the input file');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, content) VALUES (1, '800.0 dairy unload r1 100.0 bakery load r2 100.0 freezer load r1 200.0 bakery unload r1 900.0 produce load r1 1005.0 dairy unload r2 600.0 bakery unload robot_id: unique robot identifier represented as the prefix "r" with a number timestamp: timestamp (in minutes since start) zone: the warehouse zone the event is happening in event: "load" or "unload" Stage 1 The first stage must identify all zone transitions for each robot and calculate the duration of each transition . A zone transition occurs when a robot unloads in a different zone than where it loaded. It also occurs when a robot moves from a zone it unloaded into a different zone to load. Loading and unloading in the same zone is not a zone transition, nor is loading in the same zone that the robot was unloaded in. The transition duration is calculated as the difference between the timestamp when the robot arrives at the new zone and the timestamp when it was last seen in the previous zone. You may assume loading always happens prior in time to unloading for a given robot, and that every unload is preceded in time by exactly one load. However, the input file may not be sorted by the timestamp. Stage 2 The second stage must calculate the average duration for each unique transition across all robots as well as determine the slowest robot - the robot with the longest time for that path. When the same robot undergoes the same zone transition multiple times, each time counts When determining the slowest robot, you may break ties however you wish. Output For each unique zone transition path, display the transition statistics in the following format based on how many robots have taken the zone transition path. If only one robot has taken the zone transition path, the <avg_duration> and <slowest_duration> fields will be identical. <transition_path> <avg_duration> <slowest_robot> <slowest_duration> Example Output (from the input mentioned above) : bakery->produce 400.0 r1 700.0 freezer->bakery 500.0 r2 500.0 produce->dairy 102.5 r1 105.0 Constraints: Similar to how you implemented the pipeline in Project 5, write your Map and Reduce code in Python3 using the Hadoop Streaming Interface with key-value pairs separated by a tab (\t) character. Read all input from stdin and write all output to stdout. 1. You must meaningfully use all outlined stages to receive credit. You may use the identity function (no transformation) as a Map stage. 2. All Map stages must use O(1) memory to receive credit. 3. All Map stages must produce multiple groups on the sample input to receive credit. Hint: Python lists have a sort() member function. When the elements of the list are tuples, the list is sorted by the first element of the tuple, with ties broken by the second element of the tuple, and so on. # Input: [robot_id] [timestamp] [zone] [event] # Output: [robot_id]\t[timestamp] [zone] [event] for line in sys.stdin: robot_id, timestamp, zone, event = line.strip().split() # Emit robot_id as key, timestamp, zone, event as value print(f"{robot_id}\t{timestamp} {zone} {event}") # Input: [robot_id]\t[timestamp] [zone] [event] # Output: [robot_id] [zone_transition_path] [duration] def reduce_1_group(key, group): """Reduce one group for a robot.""" records = [] for line in group: robot_id, value = line.strip().split("\t") timestamp, zone, event = value.split() records.append((float(timestamp), zone, event)) # Sort by timestamp records.sort() prev_zone = None prev_timestamp = None for ts, zone, event in records: if prev_zone is not None: # prev_zone being none means the robot is first seen if prev_zone != zone: print(f"{key} {prev_zone}->{zone} {ts-prev_timestamp}") prev_zone = zone prev_timestamp = ts def keyfunc(line): """Return the key from a TAB-delimited key-value pair.""" return line.partition("\t")[0] def main(): """Divide');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, content) VALUES (1, 'Map stage. 2. All Map stages must use O(1) memory to receive credit. 3. All Map stages must produce multiple groups on the sample input to receive credit. Hint: Python lists have a sort() member function. When the elements of the list are tuples, the list is sorted by the first element of the tuple, with ties broken by the second element of the tuple, and so on. # Input: [robot_id] [timestamp] [zone] [event] # Output: [robot_id]\t[timestamp] [zone] [event] for line in sys.stdin: robot_id, timestamp, zone, event = line.strip().split() # Emit robot_id as key, timestamp, zone, event as value print(f"{robot_id}\t{timestamp} {zone} {event}") # Input: [robot_id]\t[timestamp] [zone] [event] # Output: [robot_id] [zone_transition_path] [duration] def reduce_1_group(key, group): """Reduce one group for a robot.""" records = [] for line in group: robot_id, value = line.strip().split("\t") timestamp, zone, event = value.split() records.append((float(timestamp), zone, event)) # Sort by timestamp records.sort() prev_zone = None prev_timestamp = None for ts, zone, event in records: if prev_zone is not None: # prev_zone being none means the robot is first seen if prev_zone != zone: print(f"{key} {prev_zone}->{zone} {ts-prev_timestamp}") prev_zone = zone prev_timestamp = ts def keyfunc(line): """Return the key from a TAB-delimited key-value pair.""" return line.partition("\t")[0] def main(): """Divide sorted lines into groups that share a key.""" for key, group in itertools.groupby(sys.stdin, keyfunc): reduce_1_group(key, group) if __name__ == "__main__": main() # Input: [robot_id] [zone_transition_path] [duration] # Output: [zone_transition_path]\t[robot_id] [duration] for line in sys.stdin: robot_id, zone_transition_path, duration = line.strip().split() print(f"{zone_transition_path}\t{robot_id} {duration}") # Input: [zone_transition_path]\t[robot_id] [duration] # Output: [robot_id] [avg_duration] [slowest_robot] [slowest_duration] def reduce_2_group(key, group): """Reduce one group.""" total_duration = 0 num_times_taken = 0 durations = [] for line in group: parts = line.strip().split("\t") transition, temp = parts robot_id, duration = temp.split() duration = float(duration) durations.append((duration, robot_id)) total_duration += duration num_times_taken +=1 avg = total_duration/num_times_taken durations.sort() # sort by duration, with ties broken by robot_id greatest_duration = durations[-1][0] slowest_robot = durations[-1][1] print(key, avg, slowest_robot, greatest_duration) def keyfunc(line): """Return the key from a TAB-delimited key-value pair.""" return line.partition("\t")[0] def main(): """Divide sorted lines into groups that share a key.""" for key, group in itertools.groupby(sys.stdin, keyfunc): reduce_2_group(key, group) if __name__ == "__main__": main() EECS 485 Midterm Exam Fall 2025 SOLUTION This is a 120 minute, closed-book exam. You may use one cheat sheet, 8.5”x11”, double-sided. No other notes or use of any computing or communication hardware (e.g., calculators, cell phones, smart glasses, etc.) is allowed. For multiple-choice questions, indicate your response by filling in the appropriate bubble. Fill in the bubble completely, and make sure to erase completely if you change your answer. For free response questions, write your answers clearly in the space provided in each problem. Collaboration or assistance is prohibited ● You are NOT allowed to collaborate with anyone else to answer these questions. ● You are NOT allowed to solicit assistance from anyone to answer these questions. You are to abide by the University of Michigan/Engineering Honor Code. To receive a grade, please sign below to signify that you have kept the honor code pledge. I have neither given nor received aid on this exam, nor have I concealed any violations of the Honor Code. Signature: _________________________________________ Name: _________________________________________ Uniqname: _________________________________________ UMID: _________________________________________ ◯ A. @flask.app.route(‘/film485/review/?target=/dramas/’, methods=[“GET”]) ◯ B. @flask.app.route(‘/film485/review/’, methods=[“POST”]) ◯ C. @flask.app.route(‘/film485/review/?target=/dramas/’, methods=[“POST”]) ◯ D. @flask.app.route(‘/film485/Casablanca/submit_order’, methods=[“POST”]) ◯ E. None of the above Solution: B is the only correct option, as it is performing a POST request as defined by the form “method” parameter and has the endpoint of “/film485/review”, the route pointed to by the action parameter. 5. Which of the following statements about JavaScript is FALSE? ◯ A. Out of HTML, CSS, and JavaScript, it');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, content) VALUES (1, 'in the appropriate bubble. Fill in the bubble completely, and make sure to erase completely if you change your answer. For free response questions, write your answers clearly in the space provided in each problem. Collaboration or assistance is prohibited ● You are NOT allowed to collaborate with anyone else to answer these questions. ● You are NOT allowed to solicit assistance from anyone to answer these questions. You are to abide by the University of Michigan/Engineering Honor Code. To receive a grade, please sign below to signify that you have kept the honor code pledge. I have neither given nor received aid on this exam, nor have I concealed any violations of the Honor Code. Signature: _________________________________________ Name: _________________________________________ Uniqname: _________________________________________ UMID: _________________________________________ ◯ A. @flask.app.route(‘/film485/review/?target=/dramas/’, methods=[“GET”]) ◯ B. @flask.app.route(‘/film485/review/’, methods=[“POST”]) ◯ C. @flask.app.route(‘/film485/review/?target=/dramas/’, methods=[“POST”]) ◯ D. @flask.app.route(‘/film485/Casablanca/submit_order’, methods=[“POST”]) ◯ E. None of the above Solution: B is the only correct option, as it is performing a POST request as defined by the form “method” parameter and has the endpoint of “/film485/review”, the route pointed to by the action parameter. 5. Which of the following statements about JavaScript is FALSE? ◯ A. Out of HTML, CSS, and JavaScript, it is the only programming language ◯ B. It can be used to change the Document Object Model without reloading the page ◯ C. Provides the same functionality as Python for web development ◯ B. {random number} → Number → Done ◯ C. Done → Number → random number ◯ D. Number → Done → {random number} ◯ E. None of the above 1. console.log("Number") runs first → prints Number. 2. fetch(''/api/random/int'') is asynchronous and returns a promise. The .then() callback is scheduled to run after current call stack is empty. 3. console.log("Done") runs immediately after the fetch is called → prints Done. 4. Once the network request completes, the .then() callback executes → prints a random number. Distributed Systems, MapReduce, Google File System 16. Sydney is trying to run a MapReduce program when a reducer crashes midway through processing its input. How does MapReduce ensure correctness? ◯ A. All mappers re-run to regenerate the lost input for the reducer CREATE TABLE players ( player_id INTEGER AUTOINCREMENT, name VARCHAR(20) NOT NULL, filename VARCHAR(64) NOT NULL, position VARCHAR(2) NOT NULL, drafted_manager_id INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY (player_id) FOREIGN KEY(drafted_manager_id) REFERENCES managers(manager_id) ); get_upload(filename): # serve one file in the uploads directory Simplifying assumptions: ● You can assume that the only positions in the players table are ''QB'', ''RB'', ''WR'', ''TE'', ‘K’ find_free_agents Returns a list of dictionaries for undrafted players (player_id, name, filename, position) in positions not already filled by the manager, ordered by descending player_id. def find_free_agents(drafted_manager_id): con = get_db_connection() free_agents = con.execute(""" SELECT player_id, name, filename, position FROM players WHERE drafted_manager_id IS NULL AND position NOT IN ( SELECT DISTINCT position FROM players WHERE drafted_manager_id = ? ) ORDER BY player_id DESC """, (drafted_manager_id,)).fetchall() Write the <body> section of a Jinja template for the draft page. It should include: ● The logged-in user’s team name ● The logged-in user’s current drafted team, showing each player’s profile photo, name, and position. Free Response 2: Study485 (30 points) Implement a campus study spot finder, using React functional components that allows students to see availability of study spots and report when seats open or fill up. Implement the Campus and Spot functional components. Implemented for you Campus Component Campus component: ● Declare 3 state variables: ○ spots (list) stores the list of study spots from the API. ○ locationFilter (string) representing "central", "north", or "" for both. ○ availabilityFilter (integer) representing the minimum availability to');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, content) VALUES (1, 'You can assume that the only positions in the players table are ''QB'', ''RB'', ''WR'', ''TE'', ‘K’ find_free_agents Returns a list of dictionaries for undrafted players (player_id, name, filename, position) in positions not already filled by the manager, ordered by descending player_id. def find_free_agents(drafted_manager_id): con = get_db_connection() free_agents = con.execute(""" SELECT player_id, name, filename, position FROM players WHERE drafted_manager_id IS NULL AND position NOT IN ( SELECT DISTINCT position FROM players WHERE drafted_manager_id = ? ) ORDER BY player_id DESC """, (drafted_manager_id,)).fetchall() Write the <body> section of a Jinja template for the draft page. It should include: ● The logged-in user’s team name ● The logged-in user’s current drafted team, showing each player’s profile photo, name, and position. Free Response 2: Study485 (30 points) Implement a campus study spot finder, using React functional components that allows students to see availability of study spots and report when seats open or fill up. Implement the Campus and Spot functional components. Implemented for you Campus Component Campus component: ● Declare 3 state variables: ○ spots (list) stores the list of study spots from the API. ○ locationFilter (string) representing "central", "north", or "" for both. ○ availabilityFilter (integer) representing the minimum availability to show. ● On initial render, make a GET request to /api/v1/spots/?location=<string>&minAvailability=<int> and store results in spots. ● When handling the API response: ○ Filter out any spots with availability < 0, indicating the spot is closed. ● Renders a list of Spot components, one for each study spot, with the right props (specifie d in the Spot component section). Spot Spot // compute mostAvailable return ( let mostAvailable = null; for (const s of spots) { if (mostAvailable === null || s.availability > mostAvailable.availability) { mostAvailable = s; } } ); }; export default Spot;');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, content) VALUES (2, 'Exam Directions: You have 120 minutes to complete the exam. There are 7 questions in the exam on 18 pages (double-sided). Please flip through your exam to ensure you have all pages. Write legibly and dark enough for the scanners to read your answers. Write your uniqname on the line provided at the top of each page. Exam Materials: You are allotted one 8.5 x 11 double-sided note sheet to bring into the exam room. You are allowed to use calculators that do not have an internet connection. All other electronic devices, such as cell phones or anything or calculators with an internet connection, are strictly forbidden. THIS PAGE INTENTIONALLY LEFT BLANK Completely shade the boxes with the best answer. PROBLEMS 1-5 CONTAIN POTENTIALLY MULTIPLE CORRECT ANSWERS. SELECT ALL THAT APPLY [2 points each] Which of the following are registers in a pipelined datapath that we have discussed in class? (FILL IN ALL THAT APPLY) ID/EX Mem/WB EX/WB PC FWD/WWF Which of the following methods that we have discussed in class could potentially help avoid data hazards (FILL IN ALL THAT APPLY) Detect and Stall Detect and Forward Detect and Predict Avoidance through programming and/or compilation Which of the following methods that we have discussed in class could potentially help avoid control hazards? (FILL IN ALL THAT APPLY) Delayed Branch Branch Prediction Detect and Stall Detect and Forward Which of the following combinations are legitimate cache configurations? (FILL IN ALL THAT APPLY) Write back + Write allocate Write through + Direct mapped Direct mapped + Fully associative Write back + Fully associative What are the general benefits of virtual memory (FILL IN ALL THAT APPLY) Transparency (No knowledge of how other programs are using memory) Caches (Programs are able to use caches) Protection (Programs can’t modify each other’s data) Capacity (Programs not limited by DRAM sizes) PROBLEMS 6-10 ONLY HAVE 1 CORRECT ANSWER [1 point each] Consider a program in which 50% of the instructions are loads and every load is immediately followed by a dependent ALU instruction. Also assume that there are no control hazards and all memory accesses complete in one cycle. What would be the CPI of this program run on the pipelined processor discussed in class if “Detect and Forward” is implemented? 3/2 5/2 1 5 A branch predictor is effective because branch instructions: usually (but not always) follow a predictable pattern of outcomes of taken/not-taken always follow a predictable pattern of outcomes of taken/not-taken usually (but not always) ‘hit’ in the cache always ‘hit’ in the cache always resolve before write-back Which one is true? Here we use FA to refer to Fully Associative cache, DM to refer to Direct Mapped cache, and SA to refer to a Set Associative cache that is neither FA nor DM: SA always achieves a higher cache hit rate than DM or FA. DM always achieves a higher cache hit rate than SA or FA. FA always achieves a higher cache hit rate than DM or SA. None of the above. Which of the following cache designs (assuming equal total size and number of entries) is expected to run at the lowest clock frequency if they consume the same power? Fully-associative Direct-mapped Set-associative They can all be expected to run at the same frequency How many memory accesses will each load instruction require in a system employing virtual memory and a single-level page table, but has no TLB or caches? You may ignore memory accesses involved in fetching the instruction. 1 2 3 Impossible to have virtual memory without TLB or caches. Nice try! Consider two cache designs: A');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, content) VALUES (2, 'always follow a predictable pattern of outcomes of taken/not-taken usually (but not always) ‘hit’ in the cache always ‘hit’ in the cache always resolve before write-back Which one is true? Here we use FA to refer to Fully Associative cache, DM to refer to Direct Mapped cache, and SA to refer to a Set Associative cache that is neither FA nor DM: SA always achieves a higher cache hit rate than DM or FA. DM always achieves a higher cache hit rate than SA or FA. FA always achieves a higher cache hit rate than DM or SA. None of the above. Which of the following cache designs (assuming equal total size and number of entries) is expected to run at the lowest clock frequency if they consume the same power? Fully-associative Direct-mapped Set-associative They can all be expected to run at the same frequency How many memory accesses will each load instruction require in a system employing virtual memory and a single-level page table, but has no TLB or caches? You may ignore memory accesses involved in fetching the instruction. 1 2 3 Impossible to have virtual memory without TLB or caches. Nice try! Consider two cache designs: A 1 Kilobyte 4-way associative cache with 16 byte blocks (Kilobyte = 2^10 bytes) A 1 Kilobyte direct mapped cache with 16 byte blocks Assuming the cache starts out empty, what is the smallest number of memory accesses that could result in a hit in cache A, but the exact same accesses would result in a miss in cache B. Write "N/A" if this situation is impossible [4 points] (E.g. if the 3 accesses "100, 200, 100" resulted in a hit in A but a miss in B, and no shorter set of accesses did so, you would write "3"). You don''t need to specify what addresses cause this behavior) Number of accesses: 2. Consider the 1-bit ‘last time’ branch predictor discussed in lecture. The predictor is initialized to "Not Taken". We observe the following execution sequence for a single branch: "T T N T N N N T". What is the accuracy of this predictor (provide your answer as a percentage)? Note: ‘T’ means Branch Taken and ‘N’ means Branch Not Taken. [3 points] T T N T N N N T N T T N T N N N ⅜ = 0.375 = 37.5% 3. Select all types of cache misses that apply to the following statements [5 points]: 4. Select which type of page table (compared to the other) best describes each situation [3 points]: Consider the program below: lw 0 3 four // lw1 [Line 1] lw 0 1 one // lw2 [Line 2] start add 1 1 1 // [Line 3] beq 3 1 end // beq1 [Line 4] sw 0 1 100 // sw [Line 5] beq 0 0 start // beq2 [Line 6] end halt // [Line 7] one .fill 1 // [Line 8] four .fill 4 // [Line 9] Recall the pipeline from lecture: IF → ID → EX → MEM → WB Suppose you use a modified version of the lecture pipeline. To improve cycle time, you create a new pipeline that has two MEM stages, MEM1 and MEM2, and two EX stages, EX1 and EX2. Now, the pipeline is: IF → ID → EX1 → EX2 → MEM1→ MEM2 → WB. When forwarding is allowed, data is always forwarded to EX1. When forwarding is allowed, internal forwarding from WB to ID is also present i.e. values written to a register in the WB are immediately available to reads in ID in');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, content) VALUES (2, 'cache misses that apply to the following statements [5 points]: 4. Select which type of page table (compared to the other) best describes each situation [3 points]: Consider the program below: lw 0 3 four // lw1 [Line 1] lw 0 1 one // lw2 [Line 2] start add 1 1 1 // [Line 3] beq 3 1 end // beq1 [Line 4] sw 0 1 100 // sw [Line 5] beq 0 0 start // beq2 [Line 6] end halt // [Line 7] one .fill 1 // [Line 8] four .fill 4 // [Line 9] Recall the pipeline from lecture: IF → ID → EX → MEM → WB Suppose you use a modified version of the lecture pipeline. To improve cycle time, you create a new pipeline that has two MEM stages, MEM1 and MEM2, and two EX stages, EX1 and EX2. Now, the pipeline is: IF → ID → EX1 → EX2 → MEM1→ MEM2 → WB. When forwarding is allowed, data is always forwarded to EX1. When forwarding is allowed, internal forwarding from WB to ID is also present i.e. values written to a register in the WB are immediately available to reads in ID in the same cycle. lw will finish at the end of MEM1 (i.e. when forwarding is allowed, the lw data can be forwarded from the next pipeline stage MEM2). sw will finish at the end of MEM2. add instructions will finish at the end of EX2 (i.e. when forwarding is allowed, the add data can be forwarded from the next pipeline stage MEM1). Branch address is computed in EX1 and resolved (passed to PC) in EX2. 1. Select all registers that are involved in a RAW (Read After Write) data hazard. Assume data hazards and control hazards are both resolved using detect and stall (i.e. no forwarding is allowed here). Remember, data hazards can only occur from instructions that are executed. If a register is involved in multiple hazards, list them individually. You may not need all the lines provided below. [5 points] 2. Using detect and stall to resolve data hazards, and detect and stall to resolve control hazards (again, no forwarding), what is the number of stalls due to data hazards? [4 points] Note: The old solution had errors and we have below the updated solution. We provide both below - we will accept both solutions. We will regrade for everyone. New solution: 12 if internal forwarding, 15 if no internal fwd Old solution: 16 if internal forwarding, 20 if no internal fwd 3. Using detect and forward (i.e. here forwarding is allowed) to resolve data hazards, and predict taken for branches to resolve control hazards. Answer the statements below. i. How many instructions are executed to completion in this program? [2 point] New solution: 9 Old solution: 13 ii. How many cycles does the program take to run? [3 points] New solution: 22 Old solution: 30 Consider a byte-addressable system, and a 64-byte (excluding overheads like tags / valid bits), 4-way set-associative cache with 8-byte blocks. The cache uses LRU or Least Recently Used replacement. With LRU, the way to be evicted within a set is the one that was least recently referenced. In the table, an LRU value of 0b00 denotes the least recently used way. The cache is preloaded as shown. Assume: (a) before preloading all cache entries were invalid, (b) during preloading all blocks in Set 0 were accessed before blocks in Set 1, and no evictions occurred. From this point, the following addresses are referenced. Determine whether each reference is a hit or a');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, content) VALUES (2, 'for everyone. New solution: 12 if internal forwarding, 15 if no internal fwd Old solution: 16 if internal forwarding, 20 if no internal fwd 3. Using detect and forward (i.e. here forwarding is allowed) to resolve data hazards, and predict taken for branches to resolve control hazards. Answer the statements below. i. How many instructions are executed to completion in this program? [2 point] New solution: 9 Old solution: 13 ii. How many cycles does the program take to run? [3 points] New solution: 22 Old solution: 30 Consider a byte-addressable system, and a 64-byte (excluding overheads like tags / valid bits), 4-way set-associative cache with 8-byte blocks. The cache uses LRU or Least Recently Used replacement. With LRU, the way to be evicted within a set is the one that was least recently referenced. In the table, an LRU value of 0b00 denotes the least recently used way. The cache is preloaded as shown. Assume: (a) before preloading all cache entries were invalid, (b) during preloading all blocks in Set 0 were accessed before blocks in Set 1, and no evictions occurred. From this point, the following addresses are referenced. Determine whether each reference is a hit or a miss, and categorize the type of each miss (Compulsory / Capacity / Conflict). The given first reference is not reflected in the cache, but should be updated before completing the below. Consider the following LC2K assembly program running on our 5-stage pipelined datapath from lecture. This program counts the number of zeros in the binary array Arr and stores that count in r5. Assume all registers are initialized to zero. Answer the following question 2-bit predictor = 5/10 + 5/10 + 4/10 Consider a 48-bit byte-addressable system that supports virtual memory with the following specifications (Note KB = Kilobyte = 2^10 bytes, GB = Gigabyte = 2^30 bytes): A page is 8 KB. The page table is hierarchical with 3 levels. The first-level occupies 4 pages of memory. Each second-level occupies 8 pages of memory. A page table entry is 16 B and is the same for all levels. 64 GB of physical memory is installed. You may leave your answers as exponents when appropriate [6 points] How many bits are used for the page offset? _____13___________ How many virtual pages exist in this system? ______2^35_________ How many physical pages exist in this system? ______2^23__________ How many bits in a virtual address are used to index … the first-level page table? ____11______________ a second-level page table? ____12______________ a third-level page table? ____12______________ How much memory does this page table system occupy in the worst case? Express your final answer in bytes and in powers of 2. Do not simplify (e.g. if your answer is 2x + 2y, leave it at that). [3 points] 1st PT = 2^15 B and 2^11 entries 2nd PT = 2^11*2^16 = 2^27 B and 2^11*2^12 = 2^23 entries 3rd PT = 2^23*2^16 = 2^39 B Total size = 2^15 + 2^27 + 2^39 Bytes If this system used a single-level page table instead of a three-level page table (each page table entry is still 16 bytes), how much memory would it occupy? Express your final answer in bytes and as a sum of powers of 2. Do not simplify (e.g. if your answer is 2x + 2y, leave it at that). [3 points] 2^35 entries, so 2^39 Bytes. What specific situation must occur in order for the single-level page table to use less memory than the three-level page table? Reference specific values in your answer. Limit your answer to 2 sentences. [2 points] Almost all');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, content) VALUES (2, 'virtual address are used to index … the first-level page table? ____11______________ a second-level page table? ____12______________ a third-level page table? ____12______________ How much memory does this page table system occupy in the worst case? Express your final answer in bytes and in powers of 2. Do not simplify (e.g. if your answer is 2x + 2y, leave it at that). [3 points] 1st PT = 2^15 B and 2^11 entries 2nd PT = 2^11*2^16 = 2^27 B and 2^11*2^12 = 2^23 entries 3rd PT = 2^23*2^16 = 2^39 B Total size = 2^15 + 2^27 + 2^39 Bytes If this system used a single-level page table instead of a three-level page table (each page table entry is still 16 bytes), how much memory would it occupy? Express your final answer in bytes and as a sum of powers of 2. Do not simplify (e.g. if your answer is 2x + 2y, leave it at that). [3 points] 2^35 entries, so 2^39 Bytes. What specific situation must occur in order for the single-level page table to use less memory than the three-level page table? Reference specific values in your answer. Limit your answer to 2 sentences. [2 points] Almost all or all 3rd level tables must be allocated. You are required to run a program that generates 1 Billion loads and 3 Billion stores, each accessing data that is 8 bytes in size. Your system can use a data cache with a 64-byte block which gets a 90% hit rate on that program (with some more specifications which are detailed below). Note that we are not concerned with instruction fetches or an instruction cache in this question. 1. How many bytes would be read from memory and written to memory if you did not use the data cache (write down each separately)? [3 points] 8 billion bytes read (1Billion * 8 bytes) 24 billion bytes written (3Bil * 8 bytes) Total = 32 billion Bytes 2. How many bytes of memory would be read from memory and written to memory if you had a write-through data cache with a no-write allocate policy (write down each separately)? [3 points] Reads occur only on load misses and will be at the granularity of a cache block: 1Billion * 10% * 64-bytes = 6.4 billion Bytes Writes occur on all stores and will be at the granularity of a store 3 Billion * 8 bytes = 24 billion Bytes Total = 30.4 billion Bytes 3. How many bytes of memory would be read from memory and written to memory if you had a write-back data cache with a write-allocate policy (write down each separately)? Assume 20% of all misses result in a dirty eviction. [3 points] Reads occur on all cache misses both loads and stores, at granularity of block: 4Billion*10%*64B = 25.6B Writes occur only on write back, at granularity of block: 4Billion*10%*20%*64B = 5.12B Total = 30.72 billion Bytes 4. You are allowed to make one of the two changes to the write back data cache (with write-allocate) to reduce the total bytes transferred between the cache and memory (i.e. total memory accesses). You could a) improve the data cache hit rate to 95%, or b) Reduce the dirty eviction rate on stores to 5% (loads remain at 20%). Which would you choose and why? Show calculations comparing the two changes. [5 points] (a) 95% hit rate: Total memory access in bytes = 4Billion * 64Bytes * 0.05 *(1 + 0.2) = 15.36 Billion bytes (b) Dirty eviction of stores is 5%: Total memory access in bytes = 4Billion * 64Bytes');
INSERT INTO course_chunks (class_id, content) VALUES (2, '8 bytes = 24 billion Bytes Total = 30.4 billion Bytes 3. How many bytes of memory would be read from memory and written to memory if you had a write-back data cache with a write-allocate policy (write down each separately)? Assume 20% of all misses result in a dirty eviction. [3 points] Reads occur on all cache misses both loads and stores, at granularity of block: 4Billion*10%*64B = 25.6B Writes occur only on write back, at granularity of block: 4Billion*10%*20%*64B = 5.12B Total = 30.72 billion Bytes 4. You are allowed to make one of the two changes to the write back data cache (with write-allocate) to reduce the total bytes transferred between the cache and memory (i.e. total memory accesses). You could a) improve the data cache hit rate to 95%, or b) Reduce the dirty eviction rate on stores to 5% (loads remain at 20%). Which would you choose and why? Show calculations comparing the two changes. [5 points] (a) 95% hit rate: Total memory access in bytes = 4Billion * 64Bytes * 0.05 *(1 + 0.2) = 15.36 Billion bytes (b) Dirty eviction of stores is 5%: Total memory access in bytes = 4Billion * 64Bytes * 0.1 + 1Billion* 64Bytes*10%*20% + 3Billion * 64Bytes*10%*5% = 25.6 + 1.28 + 0.96 = 27.84 Billion bytes. We would choose (a) because lower memory accesses in bytes. THIS PAGE INTENTIONALLY LEFT BLANK THIS PAGE INTENTIONALLY LEFT BLANK Final Exam _____ _____ ____ ____ __________ ___ | ____| ____/ ___/ ___| |___ /___ / _ \ | _| | _|| | \___ \ |_ \ / / | | | | |___| |__| |___ ___) | ___) |/ /| |_| | |_____|_____\____|____/ |____//_/ \___/ EECS 370 Fall 2024: Introduction to Computer Organization You are to abide by the University of Michigan College of Engineering Honor Code. Please sign below to signify that you have kept the honor code pledge: I have neither given nor received aid on this exam, nor have I concealed any violations of the Honor Code. You are to abide by the University of Michigan College of Engineer